To generate the last two symbols of the string the grammar would have to produce “… t155 t9”.

• The only non-terminal that can generate the terminal t155 is NT16 (t155 appears nowhere else on the right–hand side of a rule).  
• Therefore the subtree that covers position 13 of the string must have NT16 as its root.  
• The remaining terminal t9 can be produced only by NT16 or NT0.  
• Consequently the span “t155 t9” must be derived from one of the binary rules whose right-hand side is either  
  – NT16 NT0,  
  – NT16 NT16, or  
  – NT16 combined with some non-terminal that can later reduce to t9.

Examining every binary rule whose left-hand side is any symbol in the grammar, none has NT16 in the first position followed by NT0, NT16, or any other symbol that can reduce to t9.  
(Indeed, the only occurrences of NT0 on the right-hand side are in the pairs NT4 NT0, NT22 NT0, NT3 NT0, NT15 NT0, NT21 NT0, NT10 NT0; none of those has NT16 as the left child.  
There is also no rule with the pair NT16 NT16.)

Hence the grammar is incapable of deriving the factor “t155 t9”, which means it cannot generate the entire 14-token string.

Therefore the given string is not in the language of the grammar.
